{
  "$schema": "https://json.schemastore.org/tsconfig",

  // TOOLS ARE TYPECHECKED (DEBT-029, closed 2026-07-13).
  //
  // Until now `pnpm typecheck` covered `packages/core`, `apps/web` and `apps/functions` — and not
  // this folder. Which meant the scripts that touch the most dangerous things in the product (a
  // migration, a KVKK erasure, the break-glass tools, the verification harnesses) were the ONLY code
  // whose arguments nobody checked. A missing argument in a Server Action is a red squiggle; the same
  // mistake here was discovered by running it, by hand, against a database.
  //
  // It cost us exactly one debugging round — `verify:alpha` called `freezeEntitlement` without its
  // `from`, wrote `undefined` into Firestore and blew up in the emulator. That is the cheap version
  // of the lesson, and this file is us taking it.
  //
  // ── Why a SEPARATE project rather than adding `tools/**` to an existing one ─────────────────
  // `packages/core` and `apps/functions` are `composite` projects that EMIT — core emits its `lib/`
  // declarations, functions emits its typecheck-only `dist/`. Folding a folder of standalone scripts
  // into either would put them in an emit graph they have no business being in, and `tsc -b` would
  // start writing artifacts for files that are only ever run through `tsx`.
  //
  // So: `noEmit`, one reference to core, and its own line in the gate.
  "extends": "../tsconfig.base.json",
  "compilerOptions": {
    "noEmit": true,
    "types": ["node"]
  },
  "references": [{ "path": "../packages/core" }],
  "include": ["**/*.ts"]
}
